al and political conditions in the West; the questions of the stranger, race, and nation; her reflections on narrative, public spaces, and collectivity in the context of her engagement with Hannah Arendt's work; her development and refinement of the notions of abjection, melancholia, and narcissism in her ongoing interrogation of aesthetics; as well as her contribution to film theory. Focused primarily on Kristeva's newest work—much of it only recently translated into English—this book breaks new ground in Kristeva scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aAhmed, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeardsworth, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirmingham, Peg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandt, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChanter, Tina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChanter, Tina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDearmitt, Pleshette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcafee, Noe¨lle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliver, Kelly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPŁonowska Ziarek, Ewa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRestuccia, Frances L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZiarek, Ewa Płonowska, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruy